<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-683-819  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 683 819.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Nov 29 1990 n1241 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>; A standard style for look and feel: the drive to open systems isleading to the standardization of user interfaces.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hunter, Philip.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Varied strategies are being pursued in several segments of thecomputer industry to provide users with standardized userinterfaces for multiple applications and host systems.andP;  The trendis being driven in part by the move to open systems.andP;  Familiarexamples are the several windowing graphical user interfaces(GUIs) on microcomputers, exemplified by Microsoft Windows, theApple Macintosh GUI, Presentation Manager and the Open SoftwareFoundation's OSF/Motif.andP;  There is a trend to convergence of someof these GUIs.andP;  Digital Equipment Corp recently introduced the DECPC Lan Server 3100, which enables microcomputer users to usefamiliar products and interfaces while accessing resources on theDEC VAX VMS minicomputers.andP;  Concurrent Computer is developing areal-time version of the X-Windows GUI to provide operators with aconsistent interface for such real-time operations such as processcontrol.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     User InterfaceStandardizationTrendsWindowingGraphical User InterfaceProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>